<h3 class=3D"text-text-100 mt-3 -mb-1 text-[1.125rem] font-bold">=F0=9F=A7=
=A0 What Changed Per Breakpoint =E2=80=94 Socratic Reasoning</h3>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]"><strong>Why does mobile hide the sidebar and use a drawer instead?<=
/strong>
A 393px viewport can't afford 210px for a sidebar =E2=80=94 it would leave =
only 183px for product cards. The filter drawer slides in from the right on=
 demand, keeping full width available for content.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]"><strong>Why does mobile get a bottom navigation bar instead of a he=
ader cart button?</strong>
Thumb reach zones on a 6.7" phone make top-right buttons hard to tap one-ha=
nded. Bottom nav is the native Android pattern (and how Samsung's own apps =
work on the M36).</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]"><strong>Why does the product grid change from 2 =E2=86=92 3 =E2=86=
=92 auto-fill columns?</strong>
Mobile (2 cols) keeps cards wide enough to read specs. Tablet (3 cols) uses=
 the extra width. Desktop (auto-fill ~210px min) fills any screen naturally=
 =E2=80=94 future-proof for ultrawide monitors.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]"><strong>Why does the footer disappear on mobile?</strong>
The bottom nav replaces footer navigation. Showing both would be redundant =
and add scroll depth on a device where users expect short pages.</p>
